\sect{Outline}
\begin{itemize}
\item Introduction to fundamental algorithms of computer graphics.
\item Study implementations in general purpose language (python).
\item Study both raytracing and direct rendering.
\item See how important algorithms have been built into hardware and
  accessed by a special purpose library, OpenGL.
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\sect{Grading}
\begin{itemize}
\item 20\%: Homework assignments.  Pencil and paper, math work.  
\item 30\%: Programming assignments.  Must be on bitbucket.org
\item 10\%: Quizzes.  Every Friday except vacations and first and last week.
\item 15\%: Midterm.  Wednesday, October 29.
\item 25\%: Final.  Monday, December 8, 8:00am.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\sect{Extra Credit}
\begin{itemize}
\item Up to 10 extra credit points can be earned by doing a project.
\item Project must be proposed, in writing, to the instructor three
  weeks before the last day of class.
\item Project must be approved by the instructor, possibly with
  modifications, within 72 hours.
\item Must include a substantial programming component.
\item Must include a writeup.
\item Must include well annotated source code.
\item Must be complete and turned in before the last day of class.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\sect{Academic Dishonesty}
\begin{itemize}
\item Read Appendix D of the University Catalog.
\item Do not share code.
\item Follow the {\bf Simpson's Rule}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\sect{Bitbucket}
\begin{itemize}
\item All programs must be projects on \url{bitbucket.org}
\item Get yourself a free account immediately.
\item Add your bitbucket username to the list of names on the 
{\bf Bitbucket usernames} page on canvas.
\item Run through the tutorial
  \\\url{https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BITBUCKET/Bitbucket+101} 
\item Note: I will be testing your programs with scripts, so
the names of projects, files, functions, {\em etc.} in your code must
match exactly that specified in the instructions.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\sect{Python, pygame, numpy, pyopengl}
\begin{itemize}
\item Programming language for the course: {\bf python}
\item {\bf Pygame}:  a python package to facilitate game programming
\item {\bf Numpy}:  a python package for numerical operations, including
  linear algebra
\item {\bf Pyopengl}:  a python package wrapping the OpenGL language
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\sect{Schedule}
\begin{columns}
\column{0.5\textwidth}
1. Sept 24-26:    introduction, python, pygame, bitbucket, git

2. Sept 29-Oct 3: noise, linear algebra

3. Oct 6-10:      raytracing: intersection tests, Phong reflection
  model, normals, Whitted raytracing, texture coordinates, implicit
  surfaces, parametric surfaces, derivatives

4. Oct 13-17:     raytracing continued
\column{0.5\textwidth}
5. Oct 20-21:     transforms, direct rendering, line rendering,
  polygon filling, Phong shading

6. Oct 27-31:     Midterm Wednesday

7. Nov 3-7:       OpenGL

8. Nov 10-14:     OpenGL

9. Nov 17-21:     OpenGL

10. Nov 24-28:     OpenGL

11. Dec 1-5: Dead week.  Review

12. Dec 8:  Final exam, Monday, 8:00am.

\end{columns}
\end{frame}


